    <div class="artwork__inner">
              <dl class="specification-list">
        <dt>Gallery Text</dt>
        <dd>
        <dl>
        <dt> </dt>
        <dl><p>Smith revolutionized the sculptural process. Instead of beginning with a small-scale model, he arranged pieces of steel on the studio floor, which he had painted white for contrast, and welded them together after the central portion of the composition was complete. This method allowed him to compose free of concerns about gravity, moving parts around until the desired effect had been achieved. The light-colored background allowed him to envision the role of negative space in the finished work, an important consideration for a sculpture he intended to place in the fields outside his home. The relationship between the steel forms and the spaces between them creates a record of the artist’s movement, much as droplets of paint on a canvas trace the movement of Pollock’s arm. Doorway on Wheels exemplifies Smith’s notion of sculpture as “drawing in space,” the crux of his achievement as the preeminent American sculptor of the mid-twentieth century.</p></dl>
</dt></dl></dd></dl>


